{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01DnVNXLuAbnGnUCvbQpekCe","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Important! ES is configured to log to console (stdout), not to files. The log4j2.properties shows `appender.rolling.type = Console` - so logs go to stdout, not to files. The `/usr/share/elasticsearch/logs/` directory only has the GC logs.\n\nFor Filebeat to collect logs from the elasticsearch module, we have two options:\n1. Modify the log4j2.properties to write to files as well as console\n2. Have Filebeat read from the docker container's stdout/stderr (but in Kubernetes, this would be the pod logs, which are at `/var/log/pods/...` on the host - not accessible from a sidecar)\n3. Use Filebeat to read container stdout logs from the shared pod logs, though this is tricky since a sidecar can't directly access the host's log files without hostPath access.\n\nThe cleanest approach would be to modify the log4j2.properties ConfigMap to write logs to files in `/usr/share/elasticsearch/logs/` and share that directory between the ES container and Filebeat sidecar via emptyDir. But there's no existing ConfigMap for log4j2.properties right now—it's just the default from the image.\n\nI could create a ConfigMap with a custom log4j2.properties that writes to both console and files, mount it in the elasticsearch container, and share the logs directory with Filebeat via emptyDir. Actually, that's more standard for monitoring anyway. Let me look at what the default log4j2.properties configuration actually contains.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":757,"cache_read_input_tokens":42139,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":757},"output_tokens":20,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"se