communication.\n\nFor the monitoring cluster output, I'm using plain HTTP since it doesn't have security enabled, and I'm disabling ILM to keep the index management simple. Then I'm configuring Filebeat to collect Elasticsearch server logs and garbage collection logs from the standard log paths.\n\nContinuing with the Filebeat setup, I'm enabling the slowlog module to capture both index search and indexing slowlogs, plus deprecation warnings. The output points to the same monitoring cluster without ILM, and I'm considering whether to enable xpack in the Filebeat elasticsearch module to ensure the logs route to the proper monitoring indices for stack monitoring compatibility. the monitoring cluster. For Filebeat in 7.x, I can configure it to send monitoring data either to `filebeat-*` indices or use xpack monitoring format for `.monitoring-es-7-*` indices depending on the output settings. To keep things straightforward, I'll use Metricbeat with xpack enabled to generate the `.monitoring-es-7-mb-*` indices, and Filebeat with the elasticsearch module to create `filebeat-*` indices in the monitoring cluster.\n\nNow I'm realizing I also need to handle the Elasticsearch logging configuration. The GC logs are already being written to `/usr/share/elasticsearch/logs/`, but the application logs go to stdout because of the log4j2 configuration. I need to modify the log4j2 properties to write those application logs to files instead of just console output.\n\nWhen I update the StatefulSet to mount the new log4j2 configuration, I'll use a subPath mount just like the existing elasticsearch.yml mount, so it only replaces that specific file without shadowing the entire config directory.\n\nWriting the complete manifests... I need to configure the log4j2 properties file to use Elasticsearch's built-in property substitutions for the logs base path and cluster name, then set up the RollingFile appender to capture logs to disk.\n\nConfiguring the file appender...\n\nI'm realizing there's a naming conflict—I can't use \"rolling\" for both the console and file appenders, so I need to rename one of them to keep the configuration valid. Writing log4j2 config... I'll apply the manifests directly using kubectl with heredocs rather than creating separate files. For the StatefulSet, I need to patch multiple things at once—adding the sidecars, volumes, and volumeMounts—so I'll use a full manifest replacement instead of a strategic merge patch to keep it cleaner.\n\nWriting the patch manifest... Configuring the Filebeat container with its own config mount and read-only access to the Elasticsearch logs directory, then setting up the shared volumes including the empty directory for logs and the log4j2 configuration...\n\nI'm verifying that Kubernetes' strategic merge patch will properly handle this StatefulSet update by merging containers by name, so the existing Elasticsearch container gets the new volume mounts while the new Metricbeat and Filebeat containers are added alongside it, and all the new volumes are merged in by name as well.\n\nNow I need to write out the actual ConfigMaps and the StatefulSet patch itself. For the log4j2 configuration, I'm setting up a RollingFile appender for the server logs that Filebeat will consume, while keeping the original Console appenders intact. I should verify that Elasticsearch sets the `${sys:es.logs.cluster_name}` system property at runtime, which it does according to the source code.\n\nBefore I write all the manifests, let me step back and confirm the core requirements: each Elasticsearch pod needs both a Metricbeat sidecar for metrics collection and a Filebeat sidecar for logs, with both sending data to the monitoring cluster so the indices appear there. Let me reconsider the approach here. I'll enable Metricbeat with xpack monitoring to generate the `.monitoring-es-7-mb-*` indices, and configure Filebeat to ship logs to `filebeat-*` indices. Both approaches satisfy the requirement of getting monitoring data to the monitoring cluster—whether through stack monitoring indices or standard Beats indices, the key is that data flows there.\n\nNow I'm setting up the implementation with three ConfigMaps for the log4j2 configuration, Metricbeat, and Filebeat settings, then patching the StatefulSet to add volumes for these configs and the CA certificate, mounting them into the Elasticsearch container, and adding sidecar containers for both Metricbeat and Filebeat.\n\nWriting the configuration code... Writing kubectl commands... Configuring the rolling file appender with JSON layout, size-based rollover policies at 128MB, and setting up the root logger to use both console and file appenders, then starting to define the deprecation logging appender. Setting up the search slowlog configuration with JSON layout and message fields, then defining the logger for index search slowlog with trace level logging. Writing config patterns... Writing config template... Writing config template... Adding SAML logger configurations...\n\nI'm realizing there's a potential issue with how YAML handles the property substitution syntax - the `${sys:...}` sequences need to be preserved as literal strings so Log4j2 can interpret them when the ConfigMap is mounted into the container, rather than being processed by Kubernetes itself.\n\nThe key thing is using single quotes around the heredoc delimiter (`<<'EOF'`) to prevent bash from expanding the dollar signs during the YAML creation, which would otherwise break the Log4j2 property references.\n\nNow I'm planning out the exact sequence of kubectl commands: I'll create three ConfigMaps for the Log4j2 configuration, Metricbeat, and Filebeat, then patch the StatefulSet to mount these configs and the logs volume into the appropriate containers.\n\nI considered alternatives like using Filebeat to tail stdout or mounting the container's file descriptors, but the cleanest approach is to configure Log4j2 to write to files that Filebeat can then collect.\n\nNow I'm structuring the strategic merge patch for the StatefulSet, which needs to add volume mounts to the Elasticsearch container for both the logs directory and the Log4j2 configuration file, then inject the Metricbeat and Filebeat sidecar containers.\n\nWriting the patch JSON... Configuring the filebeat container... The strategic merge patch will merge the elasticsearch container to add new volumeMounts, introduce the metricbeat and filebeat containers, and attach the new volumes. Now I need to write out the kubectl commands, though I'm concerned about how the log4j2.properties file handles the `${sys:...}` variables—when I use a HEREDOC with `<<'EOF'` to prevent shell substitution, those literal strings get stored in the ConfigMap as-is, and log4j2 will interpret them at runtime.\n\nI also need to configure Filebeat's elasticsearch module to point to the correct log paths since the default locations won't match where Elasticsearch is actually writing logs in this setup. Configuring the Filebeat elasticsearch module to point to the mounted logs directory with the glob pattern that matches the cluster's JSON log files. I should also disable ILM in the output configuration since the monitoring cluster is a single-node setup that may not support it properly. Metricbeat handles template setup automatically when using xpack, so I don't need to configure that separately. The monitoring cluster has no security enabled, so both Metricbeat and Filebeat can output directly to it without authentication. Now I'll implement the configuration, but first I need to verify the correct flag syntax for `strict.perms` — it should be `--strict.perms=false` or `-strict.perms=false` depending on how Beats handles the flag parsing. The correct approach is to use the `--strict.perms=false` flag in the args list, though I need to verify the exact syntax for Metricbeat 7.17.x since the flag format can vary between versions. The challenge with Kubernetes ConfigMap mounts is that they default to 0644