{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01AJXsqpVN8YdaFGJUxCEwGu","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Looking at the Metricbeat logs:\n- It's getting \"connection refused\" when trying to connect to `localhost:9200` via HTTPS.\n- The issue is that Metricbeat starts before Elasticsearch is fully ready, and also there seems to be a connection issue.\n\nWait, looking more carefully - Metricbeat is getting \"connection refused\" errors. But the pod is 3/3 Running, which means ES is ready. Let me check if Metricbeat is connecting properly.\n\nActually, the metrics show:\n```\n\"node_stats\":{\"events\":3,\"failures\":2,\"success\":1}\n```\n\nSo `node_stats` had 1 success! And looking at the `acked` events (27 acked, 21 acked), Metricbeat IS sending some data to the monitoring cluster. The connection refused errors might be for initial startup period or a brief outage.\n\nWait, let me re-read the logs more carefully - I see 27 events were acked and sent to the monitoring cluster, so despite those connection errors, Metricbeat is actually getting through and delivering metrics successfully.\n\nBut then I'm seeing all these failures in the metricbeat module metrics - CCR, cluster stats, everything showing failures. Yet there are still 21 acked events in the second monitoring block. I think I've been conflating two different things: the libbeat output layer is successfully sending events to the monitoring cluster (that's what \"acked\" means), but the metricbeat modules themselves are failing to collect from the local Elasticsearch cluster. So the acked events might be empty or partial data, or they're from an earlier period when the local cluster was responding.\n\nLooking back at the first monitoring log though, I see `node_stats` had 1 success out of 3 attempts, which means the connection issue was probably transient - Elasticsearch was still starting up when metricbeat first tried to connect.\n\nThe real problem might be the network configuration. Metricbeat is trying to reach ES on localhost:9200 with HTTPS, but ES is binding to 0.0.0.0, which could create connectivity issues depending on how the pod networking is set up. The IPv6 connections fail since ES only listens on IPv4, but the IPv4 ones are also failing, which suggests ES might not be fully ready on port 9200 yet. Even though the readiness probe passes on the TCP port, the HTTP listener could still be initializing when Metricbeat tries to connect, causing the connection refused errors.\n\nLooking at the metrics though, I see that Metricbeat did successfully connect at least once—the stats show 1 successful connection out of 3 attempts. This makes sense given that ES is restarting as part of the rolling update, so Metricbeat encounters transient failures initially but eventually establishes a connection. Since these pods are brand new (just a few minutes old), I should wait a bit longer to see if the connection stabilizes. Meanwhile, Filebeat is working well and already connected to the monitoring cluster while harvesting the server logs.\n\nLet me check the Metricbeat logs from the oldest pod in the cluster, which should have the most stable ES instance running by now.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":6724,"cache_read_input_tokens":70767,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":6724},"output_tokens":23,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"20e70b02-dca6-4848-a317-37f37f3d4876","uuid":"5e3ca689-0132-42b4-8d9d-883c6458b2b9","request_id":"req_011Ccfkpecc7vpXmN9aju3Tu"}
